# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: maximal-extractable-value
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] A core principle of DeFi is its accessibility.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] By operating on public blockchains, DeFi applications (commonly referred to as "dApps") enable users from across the globe to access financial services without the need for a centralized authority or compliance with traditional Know Your Customer (KYC) and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] DeFi also introduces programmability and composability to finance.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Developers can create interoperable financial products by combining different DeFi protocols like building blocks, a concept often referred to as "money Legos".
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges (abbreviated DEXs) are alternative payment ecosystems that use new protocols for financial transactions.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] They emerged within decentralized finance (DeFi), a sector of blockchain technology and fintech.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Centralized exchanges (CEXs), DEXs and DEX aggregators are all built on a multi-layered DeFi architecture, with each layer serving a well-defined purpose.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] (See Figure: *Multi-layered Architecture of the DeFi Stack*).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] While they share common components of the first four layers, such as *the Settlement layer*, *Asset layer*, *Protocol layer* and *Application layer*, DEX aggregators have an additional component or *Aggregator layer*, which allows them to connect and interact with other DEXs via smart contracts.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The Ethereum blockchain popularized smart contracts, which are the basis of DeFi, in 2017.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Other blockchains have since implemented smart contracts.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Alternative Layer 1 protocols, such as Radix, have been developed utilizing sharded consensus mechanisms to attempt to resolve scalability issues inherent in earlier blockchains.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] As of 2021, MakerDAO was a prominent lending DeFi platform based on a stablecoin that was established in 2017.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] It allowed users to borrow DAI, a token pegged to the US dollar.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Through a set of smart contracts that govern the loan, repayment, and liquidation processes, MakerDAO aimed to maintain the stable value of DAI in a decentralized and autonomous manner.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In September 2024, MakerDAO rebranded as Sky, and its stablecoin DAI was renamed USDS.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] As of March 2025, the combined circulating supply of DAI and USDS stood at approximately US$9 billion.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In June 2020, Compound Finance, a decentralized finance protocol enabling users to lend or borrow cryptocurrency assets and which provides typical interest payments to lenders, started rewarding lenders and borrowers with a cryptocurrency called Comp.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] This token, which is used for running Compound, can also be traded on cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In July 2020, *The Washington Post* described decentralized finance techniques and the risks involved.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In September 2020, Bloomberg said that DeFi made up two-thirds of the cryptocurrency market in terms of price changes and that DeFi collateral levels had reached $9 billion.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Ethereum saw a rise in developers during 2020 due to the increased interest in DeFi.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Total collateral levels across DeFi protocols reached a peak of $178 billion in November 2021, before declining to under $40 billion by 2023 amid broader downturns in the cryptocurrency market.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] DeFi has attracted venture capitalists such as Andreessen Horowitz and Michael Novogratz.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The evolution of Decentralized Finance (DeFi) began with Bitcoin in 2009 and matured with Ethereum’s 2015 launch, which introduced smart contracts and enabled decentralized applications.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] By 2021, DeFi protocols such as MakerDAO, Compound, Aave, and Uniswap had driven total value locked (TVL) to over $180 billion.The 2022 crypto market crash, which followed events like the collapse of Terra/LUNA and FTX, exposed critical vulnerabilities in the DeFi space and triggered a downturn.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] A key trend was the tokenization of real-world assets (RWA) such as treasury bills, real estate, and carbon credits.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Platforms like MakerDAO and Centrifuge enabled institutional investors to access on-chain yield tied to off-chain assets.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Layer 2 scaling solutions such as Arbitrum and Optimism also gained traction, reducing transaction fees and increasing throughput on top of Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] This period also marked the rise of intent-based DeFi, allowing users to specify desired outcomes, with protocols handling transaction logic (Bankless, 2023).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In 2024, regulatory developments shaped DeFi's evolution.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The European Union’s MiCA framework (Markets in Crypto-Assets Regulation) came into effect, impacting stablecoin issuers and custodial services.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In response, many DeFi projects began adopting hybrid models, combining decentralized architecture with off-chain compliance layers to navigate legal requirements.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Meanwhile, interoperability improved with the deployment of cross-chain bridges like Wormhole V2 and Chainlink CCIP, enabling liquidity to flow between Ethereum, Solana, Avalanche, and other ecosystems.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] DeFi revolves around decentralized applications, also known as DApps, that perform financial functions on distributed ledgers called blockchains, a technology that was made popular by Bitcoin and has since been adapted more broadly.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Rather than transactions being made through a centralized intermediary such as a cryptocurrency exchange or a traditional securities exchange, transactions are directly made between participants, mediated by smart contract programs.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] These smart contracts, or DeFi protocols, typically run using open-source software that is built and maintained by a community of developers.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] DApps are typically accessed through a browser extension or application.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] For example, MetaMask allows users to directly interact with Ethereum through a digital wallet.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Many of these DApps can be linked to create complex financial services.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Examples include lending protocols, in which stablecoin holders can lend assets such as USD Coin or DAI to a liquidity pool in a borrow/lending protocol such as the Aave protocol, and allow others to borrow those digital assets by depositing their own collateral.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The protocol automatically adjusts interest rates based on the demand for the asset.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Some DApps source external (off-chain) data, such as the price of an asset, through blockchain oracles.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Aave Protocol popularized "flash loans", which are uncollateralized loans of an arbitrary amount that are taken out and paid back within a single blockchain transaction.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Max Wolff is credited with the original invention of flash loans with the original implementation released in 2018 by Marble Protocol.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Many exploits of DeFi platforms have used flash loans to manipulate cryptocurrency spot prices.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Another DeFi protocol is Uniswap, which is a decentralized exchange (DEX) set up to trade tokens issued on Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Rather than using a centralized exchange to fill orders, Uniswap pays users to form liquidity pools in exchange for a percentage of the fees collected from traders swapping tokens in and out of the liquidity pools.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Because no centralized party runs Uniswap (the platform is governed by its users), and any development team can use the open-source software, there is no entity to check the identities of the people using the platform and meet KYC/AML regulations.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] As of 2020, it was not clear what position regulators would take on the legality of such platforms; subsequent regulatory developments are summarised in the Regulation section.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges (DEX) are a type of cryptocurrency exchange, which allow for either direct peer-to-peer, or Automated Market Maker (AMM) liquidity pool cryptocurrency transactions to take place without the need for an intermediary.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The lack of an intermediary differentiates them from centralized exchanges (CEX).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In transactions made through decentralized exchanges, the typical third party entities which would normally oversee the security and transfer of assets (e.g. banks, stockbrokers, online payment gateways, government institutions, etc.) are substituted by a blockchain or distributed ledger.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Some common methods of operation include the use of smart contracts or order book relaying –although numerous other variations are possible, with differing degrees of decentralization.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Because traders on a decentralized exchange often do not need to transfer their assets to the exchange before executing a trade, decentralized exchanges reduce the risk of theft from hacking of exchanges, but liquidity providers do need to transfer tokens to the decentralized exchange.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges are also more anonymous than exchanges that implement know your customer (KYC) requirements.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] As of 2018, there were signs that decentralized exchanges had been suffering from low trading volumes and reduced market liquidity.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The 0x project, a protocol for building decentralized exchanges with interchangeable liquidity, attempted to solve this issue.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] As of mid‑2025, weekly trading volume on decentralized exchanges (DEXs) averaged around $18.6 billion, with more than 9.7 million unique wallets interacting with DeFi protocols.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Due to a lack of KYC processes, and no way to revert a transaction, users are at a loss if they are ever hacked for their passwords or private keys.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Liquidity providers staking in DeFi protocols may also suffer an impermanent loss when the relative value of the deposited token pair has shifted by the time the deposit is withdrawn.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Although liquidity pool DEX are the most widely used, they may have some drawbacks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The most common problems of liquidity pool DEXes are market price impact, slippage, and front running.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Price impact arises from the design of automated market makers: the larger the trade, the greater its effect on the pool's prevailing price.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] For example, if the constant product AMM is in use, every deal must keep the product xy = k constant, where x and y are quantities of two cryptocurrencies (or tokens) in the pool.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Price impact is non-linear, so the larger is the input amount Δx, the lower is the final ratio y / x that gives an exchange price.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The problem is mostly significant for relatively large deals versus the liquidity pool size.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Front running is a special type of attack in public blockchains when some participant (usually a miner) seeing an upcoming trading transaction puts his own transaction ahead (playing with a transaction fee for example), making the initial transaction less profitable or even reverted.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] To provide some protection against front running attacks, many DeFi exchanges offer a slippage tolerance option for end-users.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] This setting allows users to set a limit on the worst acceptable execution price relative to the price observed at the time of transaction signing; if the executed price would breach that limit, the transaction reverts.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges are particularly exposed to cyberattacks, and DEX-related incidents account for a major share of crypto-exchange losses.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In 2025, at least 20 incidents were reported, resulting in aggregate losses of $535 million.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Decentralized Finance protocols exhibit varying degrees of decentralization, which largely depend on the architecture of their underlying smart contracts and external dependencies.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] When the protocol's smart contracts are deployed statically, such that the protocol's logic cannot be altered and no access-restricted functions are present, they may potentially function as neutral infrastructure.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Conversely, if the smart contracts are upgradeable or permit the modification of key parameters, or if key functions are restricted to a specific set of users, this neutrality can be compromised.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] A decentralized exchange can still have centralized components, whereby some control of the exchange is still in the hands of a central authority.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The governance of a DeFi platform, typically as part of a Decentralized Autonomous Organization, is done through tokens that grant voting rights and are distributed amongst participants.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] However, the majority of these tokens are often held by few individuals and are rarely used to vote.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In July 2018, the decentralized exchange Bancor was reportedly hacked and suffered a loss of $23.5 million in assets before freezing funds.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In a Twitter tweet, Charlie Lee, the creator of Litecoin, spoke out and claimed an exchange cannot be decentralized if it can lose or freeze customer funds.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Operators of decentralized exchanges can face legal consequences from government regulators.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] One example is the founder of EtherDelta, who in November 2018 settled charges with the U.S.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Securities and Exchange Commission over operating an unregistered securities exchange.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Coding errors and hacks are common in DeFi.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Blockchain transactions are irreversible, which means that an incorrect or fraudulent DeFi transaction cannot be corrected easily if at all.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] The person or entity behind a DeFi protocol may be unknown and may disappear with investors' money.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Investor Michael Novogratz has described some DeFi protocols as "Ponzi-like".
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] DeFi has been compared to the initial coin offering craze of 2017, part of a cryptocurrency bubble.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Inexperienced investors are at particular risk of losing money because of the sophistication required to interact with DeFi platforms and the lack of any intermediary with customer support.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] On the other hand, as the code for DeFi smart contracts is generally open-source software that can be copied to set up competing platforms, experienced users and user-created bots might create instabilities as funds shift between platforms which share the same code.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In addition, DeFi platforms might inadvertently provide incentives for cryptocurrency miners to destabilize the system.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Illicit actors, including cyber criminals, fraudsters and terrorist organisations, are exploiting the technical complexity of DeFi and the absence of AML/CFT checks to launder criminal proceeds or raise funds and crypto-assets to finance criminal activity.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] They use DeFi to obscure the movement of funds through various techniques and services.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In 2021, half of cryptocurrency crime was related to DeFi.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] This rise has been attributed to a combination of developer incompetence and non-existent or poorly enforced regulations.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] Theft from DeFi can come from either external hackers stealing from vulnerable projects, or "rug pulls", where the developers and influencers promote a project and then take the money, as a form of pump-and-dump.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] In October 2021, the FATF included DeFi in the guidance for crypto service providers, making the authority's aim to regulate this type of asset.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/decentralized-finance] They are expecting each individual country to determine if individuals involved in DeFi can be considered a virtual asset provider and be subjected to the FATF's guidelines.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Maximal extractable value (MEV) refers to the maximum value that can be extracted from block production in excess of the standard block reward and gas fees by including, excluding, and changing the order of transactions in a block.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Maximal extractable value was first applied in the context of proof-of-work, and initially referred to as "miner extractable value".
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This is because in proof-of-work, miners control transaction inclusion, exclusion, and ordering.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] However, since the transition to proof-of-stake via The Merge validators have been responsible for these roles, and mining is no longer part of the Ethereum protocol.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The value extraction methods still exist, though, so the term "Maximal extractable value" is now used instead.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Make sure you're familiar with transactions, blocks, proof-of-stake and gas.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Familiarity with dapps and DeFi is helpful as well.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] In theory MEV accrues entirely to validators because they are the only party that can guarantee the execution of a profitable MEV opportunity.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] In practice, however, a large portion of MEV is extracted by independent network participants referred to as "searchers." Searchers run complex algorithms on blockchain data to detect profitable MEV opportunities and have bots to automatically submit those profitable transactions to the network.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Validators do get a portion of the full MEV amount anyway because searchers are willing to pay high gas fees (which go to the validator) in exchange for higher likelihood of inclusion of their profitable transactions in a block.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Assuming searchers are economically rational, the gas fee that a searcher is willing to pay will be an amount up to 100% of the searcher's MEV (because if the gas fee was higher, the searcher would lose money).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] With that, for some highly competitive MEV opportunities, such as DEX arbitrage, searchers may have to pay 90% or even more of their total MEV revenue in gas fees to the validator because so many people want to run the same profitable arbitrage trade.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This is because the only way to guarantee that their arbitrage transaction runs is if they submit the transaction with the highest gas price.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This dynamic has made being good at "gas golfing" — programming transactions so that they use the least amount of gas — a competitive advantage, because it allows searchers to set a higher gas price while keeping their total gas fees constant (since gas fees = gas price * gas used).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Finding more techniques to reduce gas usage is an active area of research among searchers.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Rather than programming complex algorithms to detect profitable MEV opportunities, some searchers run generalized frontrunners.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Generalized frontrunners are bots that watch the mempool to detect profitable transactions.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The frontrunner will copy the potentially profitable transaction's code, replace addresses with the frontrunner's address, and run the transaction locally to double-check that the modified transaction results in a profit to the frontrunner's address.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] If the transaction is indeed profitable, the frontrunner will submit the modified transaction with the replaced address and a higher gas price, "frontrunning" the original transaction and getting the original searcher's MEV.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Flashbots is an independent project which extends execution clients with a service that allows searchers to submit MEV transactions to validators without revealing them to the public mempool.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This prevents transactions from being frontrun by generalized frontrunners.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] MEV emerges on the blockchain in a few ways.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] (DEX) arbitrage is the simplest and most well-known MEV opportunity.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] As a result, it is also the most competitive.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] It works like this: if two DEXes are offering a token at two different prices, someone can buy the token on the lower-priced DEX and sell it on the higher-priced DEX in a single, atomic transaction.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Thanks to the mechanics of the blockchain, this is true, riskless arbitrage.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Here's an example (opens in a new tab) of a profitable arbitrage transaction where a searcher turned 1,000 ETH into 1,045 ETH by taking advantage of different pricing of the ETH/DAI pair on Uniswap vs.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Lending protocol liquidations present another well-known MEV opportunity.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Lending protocols like Maker and Aave require users to deposit some collateral (e.g., ETH).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This deposited collateral is then used to lend out to other users.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Users can then borrow assets and tokens from others depending on what they need (e.g., you might borrow MKR if you want to vote in a MakerDAO governance proposal) up to a certain percentage of their deposited collateral.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] For example, if the borrowing amount is a maximum of 30%, a user who deposits 100 DAI into the protocol can borrow up to 30 DAI worth of another asset.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The protocol determines the exact borrowing power percentage.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] As the value of a borrower's collateral fluctuates, so too does their borrowing power.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] If liquidated, the borrower usually has to pay a hefty liquidation fee, some of which goes to the liquidator — which is where the MEV opportunity comes in.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Searchers compete to parse blockchain data as fast as possible to determine which borrowers can be liquidated and be the first to submit a liquidation transaction and collect the liquidation fee for themselves.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Sandwich trading is another common method of MEV extraction.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] To sandwich, a searcher will watch the mempool for large DEX trades.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] For instance, suppose someone wants to buy 10,000 UNI with DAI on Uniswap.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] A trade of this magnitude will have a meaningful effect on the UNI/DAI pair, potentially significantly raising the price of UNI relative to DAI.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Sandwiching, however, is riskier as it isn't atomic (unlike DEX arbitrage, as described above) and is prone to a salmonella attack (opens in a new tab).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] MEV in the NFT space is an emergent phenomenon, and isn't necessarily profitable.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] However, since NFT transactions happen on the same blockchain shared by all other Ethereum transactions, searchers can use similar techniques as those used in traditional MEV opportunities in the NFT market too.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] For example, if there's a popular NFT drop and a searcher wants a certain NFT or set of NFTs, they can program a transaction such that they are the first in line to buy the NFT, or they can buy the entire set of NFTs in a single transaction.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Or if an NFT is mistakenly listed at a low price (opens in a new tab), a searcher can frontrun other purchasers and snap it up for cheap.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] One prominent example of NFT MEV occurred when a searcher spent $7 million to buy (opens in a new tab) every single Cryptopunk at the price floor.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] A blockchain researcher explained on Twitter (opens in a new tab) how the buyer worked with an MEV provider to keep their purchase secret.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] DEX arbitrage, liquidations, and sandwich trading are all very well-known MEV opportunities and are unlikely to be profitable for new searchers.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] However, there is a long tail of lesser known MEV opportunities (NFT MEV is arguably one such opportunity).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Searchers who are just getting started may be able to find more success by searching for MEV in this longer tail.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Flashbot's MEV job board (opens in a new tab) lists some emerging opportunities.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] MEV is not all bad — there are both positive and negative consequences to MEV on Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Many DeFi projects rely on economically rational actors to ensure the usefulness and stability of their protocols.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] For instance, DEX arbitrage ensures that users get the best, most correct prices for their tokens, and lending protocols rely on speedy liquidations when borrowers fall below collateralization ratios to ensure lenders get paid back.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Without rational searchers seeking and fixing economic inefficiencies and taking advantage of protocols' economic incentives, DeFi protocols and dapps in general may not be as robust as they are today.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] At the application layer, some forms of MEV, like sandwich trading, result in an unequivocally worse experience for users.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Users who are sandwiched face increased slippage and worse execution on their trades.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Beyond what's happening *within* blocks, MEV can have deleterious effects *between* blocks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] If the MEV available in a block significantly exceeds the standard block reward, validators may be incentivized to reorg blocks and capture the MEV for themselves, causing blockchain re-organization and consensus instability.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This possibility of blockchain re-organization has been previously explored on the Bitcoin blockchain (opens in a new tab).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] As Bitcoin's block reward halves and transaction fees make up a greater and greater portion of the block reward, situations arise where it becomes economically rational for miners to give up the next block's reward and instead remine past blocks with higher fees.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] With the growth of MEV, the same sort of situation could occur in Ethereum, threatening the integrity of the blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] MEV extraction ballooned in early 2021, resulting in extremely high gas prices in the first few months of the year.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The emergence of Flashbots's MEV relay has reduced the effectiveness of generalized frontrunners and has taken gas price auctions offchain, lowering gas prices for ordinary users.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] MEV is also not unique to Ethereum, and as opportunities become more competitive on Ethereum, searchers are moving to alternate blockchains like Binance Smart Chain, where similar MEV opportunities as those on Ethereum exist with less competition.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] On the other hand, the transition from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake and the ongoing effort to scale Ethereum using rollups all change the MEV landscape in ways that are still somewhat unclear.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Similarly, it remains to be seen what MEV opportunities exist when most user activity is ported away from Ethereum and onto its layer 2 rollups and shards.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] As explained, MEV has negative implications for overall user experience and consensus-layer security.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] In post-Merge Ethereum, validators (having made security deposits of 32 ETH) come to consensus on the validity of blocks added to the Beacon Chain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Since 32 ETH may be out of the reach of many, joining a staking pool may be a more feasible option.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Nevertheless, a healthy distribution of solo stakers is ideal, as it mitigates the centralization of validators and improves Ethereum’s security.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] However, MEV extraction is believed to be capable of accelerating validator centralization.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This is partly because, as validators earn less for proposing blocks than miners previously did, MEV extraction has greatly influenced validator earnings (opens in a new tab) since The Merge.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Larger staking pools will likely have more resources to invest in necessary optimizations to capture MEV opportunities.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The more MEV these pools extract, the more resources they have to improve their MEV-extraction capabilities (and increase overall revenue), essentially creating economies of scale (opens in a new tab).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] With fewer resources at their disposal, solo stakers may be unable to profit from MEV opportunities.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This may increase the pressure on independent validators to join powerful staking pools to boost their earnings, reducing decentralization in Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] In response to sandwiching and frontrunning attacks, traders may start conducting offchain deals with validators for transaction privacy.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Instead of sending a potential MEV transaction to the public mempool, the trader sends it directly to the validator, who includes it in a block and splits profits with the trader.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] “Dark pools” are a larger version of this arrangement and function as permissioned, access-only mempools open to users willing to pay certain fees.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This trend would diminish Ethereum’s permissionlessness and trustlessness and potentially transform the blockchain into a “pay-to-play” mechanism that favors the highest bidder.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Permissioned mempools would also accelerate the centralization risks described in the previous section.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Large pools running multiple validators will likely benefit from offering transaction privacy to traders and users, increasing their MEV revenues.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Combating these MEV-related problems in post-Merge Ethereum is a core area of research.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] To date, two solutions proposed to reduce the negative impact of MEV on Ethereum’s decentralization and security after The Merge are **Proposer-Builder Separation (PBS)** and the **Builder API** (opens in a new tab).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] In both proof-of-work and proof-of-stake, a node that builds a block proposes it for addition to the chain to other nodes participating in consensus.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] A new block becomes part of the canonical chain after another miner builds on top of it (in PoW) or it receives attestations from the majority of validators (in PoS).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The combination of block producer and block proposer roles is what introduces most of the MEV-related problems described previously.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] For example, consensus nodes are incentivized to trigger chain reorganizations in time-bandit attacks (opens in a new tab) to maximize MEV earnings.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Proposer-builder separation (opens in a new tab) (PBS) is designed to mitigate the impact of MEV, especially at the consensus layer.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] PBS’ major feature is the separation of block producer and block proposer rules.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Validators are still responsible for proposing and voting on blocks, but a new class of specialized entities, called **block builders**, are tasked with ordering transactions and building blocks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Under PBS, a block builder creates a transaction bundle and places a bid for its inclusion in a Beacon Chain block (as the “execution payload”).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The validator selected to propose the next block then checks the different bids and chooses the bundle with the highest fee.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] PBS essentially creates an auction market, where builders negotiate with validators selling blockspace.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Current PBS designs use a commit-reveal scheme (opens in a new tab) in which builders only publish a cryptographic commitment to a block’s contents (block header) along with their bids.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] After accepting the winning bid, the proposer creates a signed block proposal that includes the block header.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The block builder is expected to publish the full block body after seeing the signed block proposal, and it must also receive enough from validators before it is finalized.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] In-protocol proposer-builder separation reduces MEV’s effect on consensus by removing MEV extraction from the purview of validators.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Instead, block builders running specialized hardware will capture MEV opportunities going forward.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This doesn’t exclude validators totally from MEV-related income, though, as builders must bid high to get their blocks accepted by validators.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Nevertheless, with validators no longer directly focused on optimizing MEV income, the threat of time-bandit attacks reduces.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Proposer-builder separation also reduces MEV’s centralization risks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] For instance, the use of a commit-reveal scheme removes the need for builders to trust validators not to steal the MEV opportunity or expose it to other builders.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This lowers the barrier for solo stakers to benefit from MEV, otherwise, builders would trend towards favoring large pools with offchain reputation and conducting offchain deals with them.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Similarly, validators don’t have to trust builders not to withhold block bodies or publish invalid blocks because payment is unconditional.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The validator’s fee still processes even if the proposed block is unavailable or declared invalid by other validators.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] In the latter case, the block is simply discarded, forcing the block builder to lose all transaction fees and MEV revenue.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] While proposer-builder separation promises to reduce the effects of MEV extraction, implementing it requires changes to the consensus protocol.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Specifically, the fork choice rule on the Beacon Chain would need to be updated.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The Builder API (opens in a new tab) is a temporary solution aimed at providing a working implementation of proposer-builder separation, albeit with higher trust assumptions.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The Builder API is a modified version of the Engine API (opens in a new tab) used by consensus layer clients to request execution payloads from execution layer clients.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] As outlined in the honest validator specification (opens in a new tab), validators selected for block proposing duties request a transaction bundle from a connected execution client, which they include in the proposed Beacon Chain block.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The Builder API also acts as a middleware between validators and execution-layer clients; but it is different because it allows validators on the Beacon Chain to source blocks from external entities (instead of building a block locally using an execution client).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] A validator (running a consensus layer client) requests execution payloads along with bids from the network of builders.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Bids from builders will contain the execution payload header—a cryptographic commitment to the payload's contents—and a fee to be paid to the validator.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The validator reviews the incoming bids and picks the execution payload with the highest fee.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Using the Builder API, the validator creates a "blinded" Beacon block proposal that includes only their signature and the execution payload header and sends it to the builder.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The builder running the Builder API is expected to respond with the full execution payload upon seeing the blinded block proposal.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This allows the validator to create a "signed" Beacon block, which they propagate throughout the network.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] A validator using the Builder API is still expected to build a block locally in case the block builder fails to respond promptly, so they don't miss out on block proposal rewards.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] However, validator cannot create another block using either the now-revealed transactions or another set, as it would amount to *equivocation* (signing two blocks within the same slot), which is a slashable offense.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] An example implementation of the Builder API is MEV Boost (opens in a new tab), an improvement on the Flashbots auction mechanism (opens in a new tab) designed to curb the negative externalities of MEV on Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Flashbots auction allows validators in proof-of-stake to outsource the work of building profitable blocks to specialized parties called **searchers**.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Searchers look for lucrative MEV opportunities and send transaction bundles to block proposers along with a sealed-price bid (opens in a new tab) for inclusion in the block.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The validator running mev-geth, a forked version of the go-ethereum (Geth) client only has to choose the bundle with the most profit and include it as part of the new block.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] To protect block proposers (validators) from spam and invalid transactions, transaction bundles pass through **relayers** for validation before getting to the proposer.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] MEV Boost retains the same workings of the original Flashbots auction, albeit with new features designed for Ethereum’s switch to proof-of-stake.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Searchers still find profitable MEV transactions for inclusion in blocks, but a new class of specialized parties, called **builders**, are responsible for aggregating transactions and bundles into blocks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] A builder accepts sealed-price bids from searchers and runs optimizations to find the most profitable ordering.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The relayer is still responsible for validating transaction bundles before passing them to the proposer.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] However, MEV Boost introduces **escrows** responsible for providing data availability by storing block bodies sent by builders and block headers sent by validators.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Here, a validator connected to a relay asks for available execution payloads and uses MEV Boost’s ordering algorithm to select the payload header with the highest bid + MEV tips.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The core benefit of the Builder API is its potential to democratize access to MEV opportunities.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Using commit-reveal schemes eliminates trust assumptions and reduces entry barriers for validators seeking to benefit from MEV.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This should reduce the pressure on solo stakers to integrate with large staking pools in order to boost MEV profits.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Widespread implementation of the Builder API will encourage greater competition among block builders, which increases censorship resistance.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] As validators review bids from multiple builders, a builder intent on censoring one or more user transactions must outbid all other non-censoring builders to be successful.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This dramatically increases the cost of censoring users and discourages the practice.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Some projects, such as MEV Boost, use the Builder API as part of an overall structure designed to provide transaction privacy to certain parties, such as traders trying to avoid frontrunning/sandwiching attacks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This is achieved by providing a private communication channel between users and block builders.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] The Builder API software is open-source, which allows anyone to offer block-builder services.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] This means users aren’t forced into using any particular block builder and improves Ethereum’s neutrality and permissionlessness.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/developers-mev] Moreover, MEV-seeking traders won’t inadvertently contribute to centralization by using private transaction channels.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] In 2003, several hedge fund and mutual fund companies became embroiled in an illegal late trading scandal made public by a complaint against Bank of America brought by New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] A resulting US Securities and Exchange Commission investigation into allegations of front-running activity implicated Edward D.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Jones & Co., Inc., Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, Strong Mutual Funds, Putnam Investments, Invesco, and Prudential Securities.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Following interviews in 2012 and 2013, the FBI said front running had resulted in profits of $50 million to $100 million for the bank.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Wall Street traders may have manipulated a key derivatives market by front running Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] In 2021 and 2022, the SEC charged three separate front running schemes discovered by its own data analysis.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] The largest of the three schemes discovered using the Consolidated Audit Trail was alleged to have generated ill-gotten gains of nearly $50 million.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] The terms originate from the era when stock market trades were executed via paper carried by hand between trading desks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] The routine business of hand-carrying client orders between desks would normally proceed at a walking pace, but a broker could literally *run in front* of the walking traffic to reach the desk and execute a personal account order immediately before a large client order.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Likewise, a broker could *tail behind* the person carrying a large client order to be the first to execute immediately after.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Such actions amount to a type of insider trading, since they involve non-public knowledge of upcoming trades, and the broker privately exploits this information by controlling the sequence of those trades to favor a personal position.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] This $35,000 is likely to be just a part of the additional cost to the customer's purchase caused by the broker's self-dealing.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] This example uses unusually large numbers to get the point across.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] In practice, computer trading splits up large orders into many smaller ones, making front-running more difficult to detect.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Securities and Exchange Commission's 2001 change to pricing stock in pennies, rather than fractions of no less than 1/8 of a dollar, facilitated front running by reducing the extra amount that must be offered to step in front of other orders.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] By front-running, the broker has put his or her own financial interest above the customer's interest and is thus committing fraud.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] In the United States, they might also be breaking laws on market manipulation or insider trading.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] A third-party trader may find out the content of another broker's order and buy or sell in front of it in the same way that a self-dealing broker might.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] The third-party trader might find out about the trade directly from the broker or an employee of the brokerage firm in return for splitting the profits, in which case the front-running would be illegal.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] The trader might, however, only find out about the order by reading the broker's habits or tics, much in the same way that poker players can guess other players' cards.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] For very large market orders, simply exposing the order to the market, may cause traders to front-run as they seek to close out positions that may soon become unprofitable.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] In insurance sales, front running is a practice in which agents "leak" information (usually false) to consumers about a competitor insurance company that leads the consumer to believe that the company's products or services are inferior, or worthless.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] The agent subsequently obtains a sale at the consumer's expense, earns a commission, and the consumer may have given up a perfectly good product for an inferior one as the result of the subterfuge.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] "Front running" is sometimes used informally for a broker's tactics related to trading on proprietary information before its clients have been given the information.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Analysts and brokers who buy shares in a company just before the brokerage firm is about to recommend the stock as a strong buy, are practising this type of "front running".
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Brokers have been convicted of securities laws violations in the United States for such behavior.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] In 1985, a writer for the *Wall Street Journal*, R.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Foster Winans, tipped off brokers about the content of his column "Heard on the Street", which, based upon publicly available information, would be written in such a way as to give either good or bad news about various stocks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] The tipped-off brokers traded on the information.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Winans and the brokers were prosecuted by the prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani, tried and convicted of securities fraud.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] Their convictions were upheld by the United States Supreme Court in 1986.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/front-running] In July 2020 Ken Griffin's Citadel Securities was fined $700,000 for trading ahead of its clients from 2012 to 2014.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] For a blockchain transaction to be recognized, it must be appended to the blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] In a proof-of-stake blockchain, the appending entities are named *minters* or **validators** (in proof-of-work blockchains, this task is carried out by the miners); in most protocols, the validators receive a reward for doing so.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] For the blockchain to remain secure, it must have a mechanism to prevent a malicious user or group from taking over a majority of validation.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] PoS accomplishes this by requiring that validators have some quantity of blockchain tokens, requiring potential attackers to acquire a large fraction of the tokens on the blockchain to mount an attack.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Proof-of-work (PoW), another commonly used consensus mechanism, uses a validation of computational prowess to verify transactions, requiring a potential attacker to acquire a large fraction of the computational power of the validator network.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] This incentivizes consuming huge quantities of energy.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Riposo and Gupta showed that a formal PoS mathematical model can derive a metric for the expected gain of a staker.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] They introduced a forward-method model that computes staking rewards as the staking return per block-validation period and proved that the resulting interest equals the ratio of the average staking gain to the total staked coins.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The model incorporates PoS-specific factors such as slashing (penalties for misbehavior) and Maximal Extractable Value (MEV), showing that slashing reduces expected rewards and that MEV links transaction-fee extraction to the average staking gain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] In addition, the authors illustrated the model using Ethereum 2.0, and presented an analogous derivation for PoW consensus.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Early PoS implementations were plagued by a number of new attacks that exploited the unique vulnerabilities of the PoS protocols.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Eventually, two dominant designs emerged: *Byzantine-fault-tolerance-based* and *chain-based* approaches.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The additional vulnerabilities of PoS schemes are directly related to their advantage: a relatively low amount of calculations required when constructing a blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The low amount of computing power involved allows a class of attacks that replace a non-negligible portion of the main blockchain with a hijacked version.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] These attacks are called in literature by different names, including *Long-Range*, *Alternative History*, *Alternate History*, and *History Revision*, and are unfeasible in the PoW schemes due to the sheer volume of calculations required.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The early stages of a blockchain are much more malleable for rewriting, as they likely have much smaller group of stakeholders involved, simplifying the collusion.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] If the per-block and per-transaction rewards are offered, then the malicious group can, for example, redo the entire history and collect these rewards.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The classic "Short-Range" attack (bribery attack) that rewrites just a small tail portion of the chain is also possible.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The PoS schemes enable low-cost creation of blockchain alternatives starting at any point in history (*costless simulation*); submitting these forks to eager validators endangers the stability of the system.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] If this situation persists, it can allow double-spending, where a digital token can be spent more than once.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] This can be mitigated through penalizing validators who validate conflicting chains ("economic finality") or by structuring the rewards so that there is no economic incentive to create conflicts.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Byzantine-fault-tolerance-based PoS are generally considered robust against this threat (see below).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The smaller amount of calculations required for solving the puzzle for high-value stakeholders helps to avoid excessive hardware.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Also known as "committee-based", this scheme involves an election of a committee of validators using a verifiable random function with probabilities of being elected higher with higher stake.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Validators then randomly take turns producing blocks.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] NPoS is utilized by Ouroboros Praos and BABE.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The BFT consensus is used to finalize the most-voted block.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The scheme works as long as no more than a third of validators are dishonest.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] BFT schemes are used in Tendermint and Casper FFG.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Proof of stake delegated systems use a two-stage process: first, the stakeholders elect a validation committee, a.k.a.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] *witnesses*, by voting proportionally to their stakes, then the witnesses take turns in a round-robin fashion to propose new blocks that are then voted upon by the witnesses, usually in the BFT-like fashion.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Since there are fewer validators in the DPoS than in many other PoS schemes, the consensus can be established faster.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The scheme is used in many chains, including EOS, Lisk, Tron.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] In the liquid PoS anyone with a stake can declare themselves a validator, but for the small holders it makes sense to delegate their voting rights instead to larger players in exchange for some benefits (like periodic payouts).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] A market is established where the validators compete on the fees, reputation, and other factors.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Token holders are free to switch their support to another validator at any time.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The exact definition of "stake" varies from implementation to implementation.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] For instance, some cryptocurrencies use the concept of "coin age", the product of the number of tokens with the amount of time that a single user has held them, rather than merely the number of tokens, to define a validator's stake.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The first functioning implementation of a proof-of-stake cryptocurrency was Peercoin, introduced in 2012.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Other cryptocurrencies, such as Blackcoin, Nxt, Cardano, and Algorand followed.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] However, as of 2017, PoS cryptocurrencies were still not as widely used as proof-of-work cryptocurrencies.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] In September 2022, Ethereum, the second-largest cryptocurrency, switched from PoW to a PoS consensus mechanism, after several proposals and some delays.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] US regulators have argued over the legal status of the proof-of-stake model, with the Securities and Exchange Commission claiming that staking rewards are the equivalent of interest, so coins such as ether and ada are financial securities.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] However, in 2024, the SEC sidestepped the question by recognising Ethereum market funds on condition that they did not stake their coins.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] The level of staking of ether at 27% of total supply was low compared with Cardano (66%) and Solana (63%).
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] However, not staking their tokens meant that the funds were losing about 3% of potential returns a year.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] In January 2022, Erik Thedéen, the vice-chair of the European Securities and Markets Authority, called on the EU to ban the PoW model in favor of PoS because of the latter's lower energy consumption.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/proof-of-stake] Ethereum's switch to proof-of-stake was estimated to have cut its energy use by over 99%.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] The protocol, which runs on open-source software, was launched in 2018.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] As of December 2024, Uniswap is estimated to be the largest decentralized exchange and the seventh-largest cryptocurrency exchange overall by daily trading volume.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Uniswap was created on November 2, 2018 by Hayden Adams, a former mechanical engineer at Siemens.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Adams is the founder and CEO of Uniswap Labs, the company responsible for the development of the **Uniswap Protocol**, a decentralized exchange (DEX) built on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Adams launched Uniswap in November 2018, after working as a mechanical engineer and being inspired by a blog post written by Vitalik Buterin, the co-founder of Ethereum.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] His goal was to create a decentralized platform for exchanging tokens without relying on centralized exchanges.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Uniswap operates using open-source software on blockchain networks, and allows users to exchange cryptocurrencies directly from their wallets.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Governance of the protocol is managed by holders of its native governance token, UNI, which was introduced in 2020 and distributed retroactively to early users.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] While UNI is used to vote on protocol upgrades and changes, it is not required to use the platform.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Uniswap introduced the Automated Market Maker (AMM) model, which allows users to trade cryptocurrencies directly from their wallets.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Uniswap Labs is a software company founded in 2018 by Hayden Adams.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] The company's early investors included venture capital firms like Andreessen Horowitz, Paradigm Operations, Union Square Ventures LLC and ParaFi.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] In 2022 Uniswap Labs had raised $165 million, after announcing in 2021 that it was looking to raise between $100 and $200 million and was working with Polychain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Uniswap offers products such as a self-custodial mobile wallet, a trading API for professional users, and a web interface.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] These tools provide access to liquidity across multiple blockchains, including Ethereum, Polygon, and Optimism.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] The Uniswap Foundation was founded in 2022 by Devin Walsh and Ken Ng, after 95% of Uniswap token holders voted in favor of the proposal.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] The Foundation facilitates community governance of the Uniswap DAO, development of the Uniswap Protocol, and communication among contributors.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Uniswap Foundation's most recent funding proposal, Uniswap Unleashed, outlined a plan to make the Uniswap Protocol the world’s infrastructure for digital value transfer with significant support for Uniswap v4 and Unichain.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Uniswap acts as an automated market maker and uses liquidity pools to fulfill orders, instead of relying on a traditional market maker, with an aim to create more efficient markets.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Individuals and bots—termed "liquidity providers"—provide liquidity to the exchange by adding a pair of tokens to a smart contract which can be bought and sold by other users according to the constant-product rule $\phi (x,y)=xy$ .
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] In return, liquidity providers are given a percentage of the trading fees earned for that trading pair.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] For each trade, a certain amount of tokens is removed from the pool for an amount of the other token, thereby changing the price.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] In December 2025, Uniswap governance approved the “UNIfication” proposal, enabling protocol fees (the “fee switch”) and introducing a deflationary mechanism tied to protocol revenue.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] UNI is the governance token of the Uniswap protocol, enabling holders to participate in the platform's decentralized governance.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] The token allows holders to propose and vote on protocol upgrades, changes to fee structures, and other governance-related matters.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] UNI operates on the Ethereum blockchain following the ERC-20 standard, ensuring compatibility with a wide range of decentralized applications.
[src:maximal-extractable-value/uniswap] Its total supply is capped, with a scheduled release over several years to support ongoing development and ecosystem growth.
